VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I\'m going to notify on a new order. Simple name, it has my purpose, and I will select everything from items in the collection we made called orders. Now, I can build out a trigger, and for the'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trigger, I hook into when a new item is created, specifically in that orders collection. So, now every time a new order comes in, something is going to happen. I\'m going to add in an operation. We\'re going to send an email.'

[03:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s going to write a subject. I\'m going to add my email to this, and then in the body, I\'m going to pull in the order data. So, anytime a new order goes in, it\'s going to push that data through into an email. Now, I can save this operation, and we\'re going to save the'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'flow, and we\'re done. Okay, now watch this. I\'m going to go back, and in my starting Docker Compose file, I added Mailpit to test this out. This is just a super simple way to test out that email send function. When I make one more'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'order, just like before, nothing fancy, but this time, something is different. This now triggers the flow automatically, and an email goes out with the details. There\'s no back end logic here. There\'s no wiring things'

[04:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'together. This started as nothing, no tables, no back end, no real structure here, and in just a few minutes, it\'s a working app with data, permissions, and yes, automation, which was the cool part. And this is what makes Directus'

[04:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'feel pretty cool. It\'s almost like a combination of visual database logic with something like n8n or Zapier built in, but that\'s not really who it competes with. So, what is Directus exactly? It\'s an open source data'

[04:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'platform that sits on top of your SQL database. It doesn\'t sit beside it, it sits on top of it. That database first model is the whole point, right? So, what does this really mean? Well, it'

[04:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'means a few things for us. It means there\'s no lock-in, the full SQL is still there, and it works with legacy systems. That\'s why people use it for things like SaaS back ends, internal tools, headless CMS setups, AI agents'

[05:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with controlled data. You\'re trying to modernize some old system without rewriting everything. Your database is the actual engine here. Directus just gives it a dashboard and controls. Now, at first glance, if you played with'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other tools like Strapi, Payload, Hasura, and Directus is going to look similar to this, but they actually solve different problems. Strapi and Payload are code first. You define the schemas in code, then rebuild your structure'

[05:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there. Yeah, that does work, but it\'s extra work. Directus changes a few things with some tweaks. Your schema already exists, so instead of recreating it, you just connect it. Different workflow entirely here. Hasura is great'

[05:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for fast GraphQL, but Directus goes even wider than just this. You\'re getting APIs. Yes, we do get that, but we\'re also getting admin workspace, permissions, files, and automations. And'

[06:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here\'s the part most devs care about after trying it out. Permissions. I\'m not talking about just rules here, right? We\'re talking about real control with no plugins. So, if your problem is I need back end, you\'ve got options. If'

[06:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your problem is I don\'t want to rebuild my back end again, this is different. Now, obviously, no tool is perfect, but this is pretty neat. What did I think was super cool? Well, the permissions just work, that\'s awesome. Flows remove'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a lot of the busy work we\'re doing. The UI was really clean and fast, and it\'s easy to deploy with Docker. On top of all that, it scales really well. But with all this good stuff, of course,'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there\'s always these drawbacks. So, the tradeoffs are going to be things like advanced flows can take time, right? If you\'ve ever played with n8n, anything else, you get it. Docs are not always there. And if you self-host, you need to manage the infra yourself. Plus, complex'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'setups can get messy locally. Directus just removes a very specific kind of repeated back end work. So, is Directus worth it? For a lot of us, probably yeah, depends on what we\'re doing, especially if you already have SQL data,'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or if you\'re tired of rebuilding these basic back ends we\'re doing all the time over and over, then yeah, this is some real value. It saves time, it reduces maintenance, and you keep control of the data. Once again, it\'s open source. We'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'control that. When would you not use this? Well, if you\'re in a strict TypeScript, like a huge mono repo, probably not, right? If you don\'t have an existing database, probably not. If you want everything defined in code from'

[07:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the start, then something like Payload just makes a lot more sense here. But if you\'re thinking right now, wait, this can just sit on top of my database, yeah, it can. So, it might be worth trying. If you enjoy open source tools and coding tips like this one, be sure'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
